model_explanation: if Sam only gave Bill bananas, then giving him grapes contradicts that exclusivity.
saying Sam only gave Mary apples excludes the possibility that he gave apples to others like Ellen, so the second statement contradicts the first.
if Sam only gave Sue apples, this excludes giving apples to Tom, so the second sentence contradicts the first.
if Sam only gave Bill grapes, that means he didn’t give him anything else, so the statement that he didn’t give Bill oranges is entailed.
if Sam only gave Bill apples, then it must be true that he didn’t give Bill bananas, which is entailed by the first sentence.
if Sam only gave Sue apples, that logically entails that he didn’t give her bananas or anything else besides apples.
the statement about Sam only giving Ellen oranges doesn’t provide information about whether Tom got oranges, so the second sentence is independent.
if Sam only gave Tom apples, then by definition he didn’t give apples to anyone else, including Mary, so it’s entailed.
if he only gave apples to Tom, then giving them to Bill contradicts that exclusivity.
if Sam only gave Sue bananas, then it necessarily follows that he didn’t give them to Tom, so it’s entailed.
